<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="11" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,151,1598]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<emphasis box="[199,297,1435,1459]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Remarks</emphasis>
: This new species resembles 
<taxonomicName authority="Schumacher" authorityName="Schumacher" authorityYear="1915" box="[631,1003,1434,1459]" class="Insecta" family="Issidae" genus="Gergithus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bistriatus">
<emphasis box="[631,768,1435,1459]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">G. bistriatus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Schumacher" box="[783,1003,1434,1458]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" refString="Schumacher, F. (1915) Homoptera in H. Sauter's Formosa-Ausbeute. Supplementa Entomologica, 4, 108 - 142." type="journal article" year="1915">
Schumacher), 
<number box="[947,1003,1434,1458]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" value="1915.0">1915</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
from which it can be distinguished by the three black oblique stripes on tegmen and one black spot at apical third of tegmen, whereas in 
<taxonomicName box="[1251,1388,1469,1493]" class="Insecta" family="Issidae" genus="Gergithus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bistriatus">
<emphasis box="[1251,1388,1469,1493]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">G. bistriatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the tegmen has two transverse brown bands medially and on apical third, always interrupted, and with a brown spot at apex. The two species also differ in male genitalia.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1011,1573,1598]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,151,1598]" box="[199,1011,1573,1598]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<emphasis box="[199,319,1573,1597]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Etymology</emphasis>
: The specific epithet refers to the three stripes on the tegmen.
</paragraph>
